              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Understanding Fatty Liver Disease</h5>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                Non-Alcoholic Fatty Liver Disease (NAFLD) occurs when excess fat accumulates in the liver in people who drink little to no alcohol. It affects up to 25-30% of the general population and is closely linked to obesity, insulin resistance, type 2 diabetes, and metabolic syndrome. NAFLD can progress to Non-Alcoholic Steatohepatitis (NASH), where inflammation and liver cell damage occur alongside fat accumulation.
              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">NAFLD vs NASH</h5>
              <ul class="list-items list-unstyled mb-40 pl-40">
                <li><strong>Simple Fatty Liver (NAFLD):</strong> Fat accumulation without significant inflammation or liver damage. Usually benign with low risk of progression.</li>
                <li><strong>NASH (Non-Alcoholic Steatohepatitis):</strong> Fat accumulation plus inflammation and liver cell injury. Can progress to fibrosis, cirrhosis, and liver failure.</li>
              </ul>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Risk Factors and Causes</h5>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                Key risk factors include obesity (especially abdominal obesity), type 2 diabetes, insulin resistance, metabolic syndrome, high cholesterol and triglycerides, polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), sleep apnea, hypothyroidism, and certain medications. Age over 50 and family history also increase risk.
              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Diagnosis and Assessment</h5>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                Diagnosis involves blood tests (liver enzymes, lipid profile, glucose), imaging (ultrasound, CT, MRI, FibroScan), and sometimes liver biopsy to determine the extent of inflammation and fibrosis. We use non-invasive tests like FibroScan to assess liver stiffness and fat content.
              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Treatment Approach</h5>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                <strong>Weight Loss:</strong> Even a 5-10% reduction in body weight can significantly improve liver health and reduce fat accumulation.
              </p>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                <strong>Diet Modifications:</strong> Mediterranean diet, reduced refined carbohydrates and sugars, increased fiber, and avoiding fructose-sweetened beverages.
              </p>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                <strong>Exercise:</strong> Regular physical activity (150 minutes/week) improves insulin sensitivity and reduces liver fat.
              </p>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                <strong>Manage Associated Conditions:</strong> Control diabetes, high cholesterol, and blood pressure with appropriate medications.
              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Prevention of Progression</h5>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                Regular monitoring is essential to detect progression to NASH or fibrosis. Avoid alcohol completely, maintain healthy weight, control metabolic conditions, and follow up regularly with your hepatologist. Early intervention can prevent progression to cirrhosis and liver failure.
              </p>
